AGI - Almost eight out of ten Europeans (77%) are in favour of a common security and defence policy for EU countries, while just over seven out of ten (71%) agree that Brussels should strengthen its ability to produce military equipment and invest in the defense industry.
These are the results of the last Eurobarometer published today by the European Commission two weeks by the Elections, with almost three quarters of the respondents (74%) who declare to feel European citizens, the highest level in over two decades. "It is a very encouraging data," said EU Vice-President Margaritis Schinas today at a conference at the Brussels European Forum.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The survey also shows that 69% are in favour of a common foreign policy of the Member States. For 34% of Europeans, security and defence are the priority sector for medium-term EU action, followed by climate and environment (30%). Health is in third place with 26% and the economy and migration to the fourth (both 25%). At the same time, almost half (46%) of citizens believe that ensuring peace and stability will have the greatest positive impact on their lives, followed by the safety of food, health and industrial supplies in the EU (28%), the creation of greater employment opportunities and the management of migration flows (26%).
<h2> Support for Ukraine
More than two years after the launch of the current massive military invasion by Russia, almost nine out of ten (87%) agree that the EU should provide humanitarian support to those who suffer for the effects of war and more than eight out of ten (83%) agree in welcoming people fleeing war in Europe. 72% of citizens are in favour of economic sanctions against government, companies and individual Russian individuals while 70% agree to provide financial support in Kiev.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
60% approves that the Brussels authorities grant Ukraine the status of candidate country and finance the purchase and supply of military equipment in support of the army led by the Zelensky government. Among the most recent crises, it is the Russian invasion of Ukraine to have influenced more the way in which European citizens look to the future (42%), followed by pandemic and other health crises (34%), as well as the economic and financial crisis (23%). On a list of 15 issues the EU faces, the war in Ukraine is identified as one of the two most important problems since 35% of respondents, seven percentage points more than last November. Immigration follows (24%), the international situation (22%) and inflation (19%).
<h2> How the economy goes
The perception of the state of the European economy has improved since autumn 2023, with 47% of respondents now assessing the situation as "good", the highest level since 2019. 45% of respondents believe that the European economic situation will remain stable in the next twelve months. This positive trend is also reflected in constantly high support for the euro, both in the EU as a whole (70%) and in the euro area (78%). More than six out of ten European citizens (62%) are also optimistic about the future of the EU, with a slight increase compared to the previous autumn 2023 survey. Confidence in the European institutions has also increased and is now at 49%, while that in national governments is at 33%. Finally, almost six out of ten people are satisfied with the functioning of democracy in the EU (57%) and in their country (58%), according to the Eurobarometer survey conducted between 3 and 28 April on 26,399 people in the 27 Member States.
